class Solution {
    public long maximumScoreAfterOperations(int[][] edges, int[] values) {
        List<Integer>[] g = new ArrayList[values.length];
        Arrays.setAll(g, e -> new ArrayList<>());
        g[0].add(-1); 
        for (int[] e : edges) {
            int x = e[0], y = e[1];
            g[x].add(y);
            g[y].add(x);
        }
        long ans = 0;
        for (int v : values) {
            ans += v;
        }
        return ans - dfs(0, -1, g, values);
    }

    private long dfs(int x, int fa, List<Integer>[] g, int[] values) {
        if (g[x].size() == 1) {
            return values[x];
        }
        long loss = 0;
        for (int y : g[x]) {
            if (y != fa) {
                loss += dfs(y, x, g, values);
            }
        }
        return Math.min(values[x], loss);
    }
}
In the solution, we first create a graph based on the edges. Then we calculate the total sum of the values. Then we perform a depth-first search (DFS) on the graph starting from the root node (0). During the DFS, we calculate the loss of the path from the root to any leaf node. We return the minimum value between the value of the current node and the loss. The maximum score is the total sum of the values minus the loss.

