class Solution {
    public int numberOfPairs(int[][] points) {
        int pairs = 0;
        Arrays.sort(points, (a, b) -> {
            if (a[0] != b[0]) {
                return a[0] - b[0];
            } else {
                return b[1] - a[1];
            }
        });
        int n = points.length;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            for (int j = i + 1; j < n; j++) {
                if (isGood(points, i, j)) {
                    pairs++;
                }
            }
        }
        return pairs;
    }
    public boolean isGood(int[][] points, int index1, int index2) {
        int n = points.length;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if (i == index1 || i == index2) {
                continue;
            }
            if (points[i][0] >= points[index1][0] && points[i][0] <= points[index2][0] && points[i][1] >= points[index2][1] && points[i][1] <= points[index1][1]) {
                return false;
            }
        }
        return true;
    }
}
```
In the above code, we first sort the points in ascending order of x-coordinate and then descending order of y-coordinate. Then we iterate over all pairs of points and for each pair, we check if the pair is good. If it is, we increment the count of pairs. A pair is good if there are no other points in the rectangle or line they make (including the border). This is done in the `isGood` method.

